SIMPLE: susceptibility
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Susceptibility
<hw>Sus*cep`ti*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Susceptibilities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>susceptibilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The state or quality of being susceptible; the capability of
receiving impressions, or of being affected.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, capacity for deep feeling or emotional
excitement; sensibility, in its broadest acceptation; impressibility;
sensitiveness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magnetic susceptibility</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld>,
<cd>the intensity of magnetization of a body placed in a uniform
megnetic field of unit strength.</cd> <au>Sir W. Thomson.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Capability; sensibility; feeling;
emotion.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Susceptible</ent>⟦br⟧
